== <span class="header">Description</span> ==

{{Blurimage|file=Gone.jpg|caption=Level 76 at night after snow. This is one of the most well-known pictures of this level.|hovertext=It's gone.}}

Level 76 is an endless road winding through the hills of a boreal forest. It is lined with wire mesh fences, flickering lampposts, old wooden power lines, and occasional sections of cracked sidewalk. The road is typically made of asphalt or concrete with no junctions, crossings, or street signs to be found. The forest beyond is navigable, but any extended travel through it leads back to the same road no matter which direction is chosen.

It should be noted that this level is under the effects of [[Phenomenon 15]]; meeting other explorers is not possible.

The level has a normal, 24-hour day-night cycle. Temperatures vary from day to day, reaching highs of approximately 13°C (55°F) or falling to an uncomfortable -12°C (10°F). The sky is perpetually overcast, with daytime bringing diffuse sunlight and chilly winds to clear the fog that tends to accumulate at night. Precipitation can be expected during other nights, which can include rain, mist, snow, or hail, and which often continues well into the morning. Because blizzards can cause fast and considerable snow buildup, one should travel with suitable winter gear to ward off frostbite.

The road clearly displays [[Phenomenon 14|shifting geometry]]; traveling in a single direction and then retracing one's steps can lead to a completely different place. Several explorers have experienced additional anomalies, such as distant objects not appearing to get any closer during long straightaways. Others describe more intense distortions where the path narrows to a startling degree and is covered by a dense canopy. By far the most common claim is hearing movement or another set of footsteps near or behind oneself while walking, despite the absence of any companions or entities. There have been no proven recordings of any of these phenomena. Be advised that Level 76 may not be as stable as it seems, and that prolonged travel may promote hallucinations.

At times, it is possible to come across small groups of empty lots and clearings along the road. Within them, there are large patches of dirt and exposed foundation, suggesting the former presence of buildings. Street and business signs may be found nearby, as well as flyers affixed to lampposts and power lines. All of these are blank, leaving the purpose and identity of the missing buildings a mystery. There is little to no weathering or debris among any of these features; nothing appears to have been destroyed.

Many people have experienced reminiscence, recognition, and déjà vu when exploring the empty lots. It is unclear whether this is a phenomenon caused by the level or a natural effect of the circumstances and repetitive environment.

=== <span class="header">The House</span> ===

Among the empty lots, it is not uncommon to find a well-maintained side path leading to a house. It can generally be described as a contemporary suburban home. Any finer details of the exterior are unique to each explorer but stay the same every time it is encountered. Regardless of the outside, the inside of the house is similar for everyone: larger than the outside, consisting of several distinct interiors linked together by open doorways, although the layout of the rooms may vary. The front, back, and any side doors of the house (including the garage if applicable) can lead to any of these interiors through their correspondences.

The inside of the house appears neglected or recently abandoned. The lightbulbs are burned out, but electricity still flows from the wall sockets. Grime collects in the bathrooms, but the taps still run clean water. The air is rather dusty, and a layer of it covers most surfaces, but it is not unbreathable. Additionally, similar to the exterior, the exact features of the interior also differ between visitors, but this is usually limited to the presence, absence, or arrangement of various objects such as furniture, cardboard boxes, and assorted tools, appliances, and packages.

The house has no confirmed spatial anomalies aside from the ones mentioned prior, although other phenomena are reported semi-frequently. The following paragraphs describe the most consistent ones, but keep in mind the possibility of unexpected events when exploring.

Rooms that are not directly observed may produce sounds of intermittent activity such as footsteps or shuffling objects, but these cease when direct observation or recording is attempted. Muffled voices are rarely heard among these sounds, the owners of which are consistent and sometimes include people who have previously entered Level 76. Voices most often emanate from a locked room on the uppermost floor of the house, although picking or forcing it open reveals it to be an otherwise ordinary bedroom.

Kitchen pantries and refrigerators are empty when first arriving at the house, but they gradually fill up over the duration of one's stay. New foodstuffs appear spread between each kitchen at a rate of approximately 2 – 5 items per day, and they stop appearing when there is not enough space for more. The guarantee of food would make Level 76 an appealing option for settlement were it not for the lack of human contact.

Some explorers report the presence of a slow but serviceable Wi-Fi signal and even a single [[Phenomenon 2|BACK-NET]] terminal within the house, but just like its other features, these are not guaranteed. The presence of routers inside certain offices does not appear to correlate with Wi-Fi signal strength.

When one leaves and returns to Level 76, the house and its contents will have returned to the state they were first found in. Food items vanish entirely, while other belongings are scattered amongst the clutter, boxes, and drawers. Finding them again may be difficult due to the size of the house, so when departing, it is recommended to take out everything that was brought in.

== <span class="header">Colonies & Outposts</span> ==

Due to [[Phenomenon 15]], no colonies or outposts can be created in Level 76. However, the level's house serves as a reliable long-term rest stop due to the accumulation of food.

Some people choose the house as a permanent albeit solitary place of residence. Many who attempt this are unable to bear the resulting loneliness. It is unclear how many people are currently living in their own instances of Level 76.

== <span class="header">Transit</span> ==

=== <span class="header">Entrances</span> ===

{{Blurimage|file=76road2.png|caption=A long straightaway found while entering the level.|hovertext=Keep moving forward.}}

* The main road can appear in any of the following places, indicating a natural transition into Level 76. This list is not exhaustive.
** [[Level 72|Level 72 "The Worm in the Fruit"]]
** [[Level 73|Level 73 "Shooting Gallery"]]
** [[Level 75|Level 75 "Indigence"]]
** [[Level 78|Level 78 "Psychological Planet"]]
** [[Level 79|Level 79 "Strums of Suburbia"]]
** [[Level 82|Level 82 "Light Pollution"]]
** [[Level 107|Level 107 "Xaorézhǚ"]]
* Noclipping in the following places and conditions commonly leads to Level 76, which is always covered in snow upon arrival.
** Anywhere in [[Level 74|Level 74 "Australis"]].
<!--** Anywhere during the "Winter Wonderland" event of [[Level 191|Level 191 "Midnight Stroll at Low Tempest"]].-->
<!--** Anywhere in the Forsaken Tundra of [[Level 206|Level 206 "Mirage Violet"]], when alone.-->
** Inside any building in [[Level 449|Level 449 "It's Snowing Like It's the End of the World"]].
* Some sliding glass doors in [[Level 798|Level 798 "Serene Skylights"]] open into Level 76.
* Falling asleep in any snowy level has a very small chance to bring one here. When this happens, sleeping outside results in waking up on the road or in an empty lot, while sleeping indoors leads directly to the house.

=== <span class="header">Exits</span> ===

* During warmer days, it is possible for the road to eventually end at [[Level 77|Level 77 "Acceptance"]]. The window of time for this is signaled by the onset of thick fog.
* During rainy nights, the road sometimes transitions into that of [[Level 124|Level 124 "Somber Streets"]]. This is indicated by the rain becoming increasingly lukewarm.
* Noclipping into the snow can lead to any of the following places.
** [[Level 65|Level 65 "Hyperborea"]]
** [[Level 634|Level 634 "Velglace"]]
** [[Level 797|Level 797 "Alpine Village"]]
* At dusk, the sky in Level 76 can turn red for up to several hours. While this is a rare event, new hallways appear in the house at this time, which lead to buildings in [[Level 93|Level 93 "Erythrophobia"]]. Passing through the forest also leads to Level 93, but the oncoming erythrophobia from that level can be dangerous without shelter.
* Very rarely, a single tree in the forest may be covered in Christmas decorations. Noclipping near or into it leads to [[Level 125|Level 125 "Desolate Holiday"]].

<center style="font-family: Edu AU VIC WA NT Hand; font-style: italic; font-size: 22px">Why did you come here when you're just going to leave? To leave me, like everyone else?</center>

== <span class="header">Addendum 1</span> ==

Shortly after the discovery of Level 76 in early 2003, explorers began finding lone scraps of paper in various places throughout the level. <s>They remain a fairly predictable occurrence, being found roughly once every week during extended stays.</s> They can appear in many places, such as taped to lampposts, trees, or fences, stashed in a drawer inside the house, or left crumpled and alone in the middle of the road. They may not be present upon first observation of these places.

These pieces of paper appear to be torn out of something larger, such as books or newspapers. A portion of the text, often in the center or near one of the edges, has its original content missing or scratched out, only to be replaced by a handwritten message. These messages are brief, being no longer than a few short sentences, and often show concern for the comfort and well-being of the recipient. Alternatively, they may convey a sense of loneliness and be pleading for the reader to stay within Level 76.

Below is an example list of notes that have been collected by various explorers.

* ''"Welcome back. I missed you."''
* ''"Rest here for a while. You look like you need it."''
* ''"It's too cold out there. Come inside."''
* ''"Won't you keep me company?"''
* ''"You're lost. Wandering without care. I understand."''
* ''"I'm sorry I don't have the energy to clean this place up."''
* ''"Just a little longer. Please. I don't want to be alone again."''
* ''"I know you want to retreat, but they need you more than I do. It's time for you to go."''

It is believed that the intended recipient of each message is, in fact, the wanderer who receives them. This is due to the personalized nature of the original contents of each scrap of paper. Most are articles describing the past activity of the reader or the people they know (from the Frontrooms or otherwise), such as interviews with family members, a list of the reader's goals and desires, or a narrative of what they were doing at an indeterminate point in the past, including moments before finding the message. There are many instances of exceedingly personal documents as well, such as letters, gift receipts, yearbook pages, medical reports, and birth certificates.

Whether or not any of these truly come from the Frontrooms is unknown. The authors of both the articles and the handwritten messages are unknown. Many have speculated that they may be connected, or even the same individual, although such claims cannot be verified as of writing.

== <span class="header">Addendum 2</span> ==

The following is a transcript of a journal entry posted to [[Backchat (Collaborative Log)|Backchat]] in November 2008 by a throwaway account. An additional photo of Level 76 was included. It quickly garnered attention among users, becoming a major contributor to the overall public knowledge of Level 76. Unfortunately, the poster's account was hacked and the post was deleted, leaving only screenshots and transcripts such as this one.

<div class="light-borderblock">
{{Blurimage|file=Theendimage.png|caption=Whose tracks are these?|hovertext=Is somebody here?}}

October 20, 2008

Everything has been so stressful.

I don't remember who started it, or when. We were supposed to be a team. Working together. Keeping each other alive. Being there when things go wrong. I should've known better than to trust them. Or myself. They kept wasting resources, but they just wouldn't listen. It almost got us killed. On so many occasions that I'm tired of writing about them. And they all gave so many excuses.

I hate when people lie. Everyone always lies. Everything in this godforsaken <del>universe</del> <del>realm</del> dimension <del>whatever</del> always lies. And when we believe it, we pay with our blood. You don't get this kind of cruelty in the Frontrooms. Nobody in their right mind stoops this low. Nobody that I know (except my own goddamn team, but this isn't the Frontrooms is it?)

We all got separated for a while. The tension just kept growing, I couldn't calm them down, they started shouting, and I just ran away. Again. I couldn't find my way back, and I wanted to scream. So when I saw the forest road, I ran straight into it. I wasn't thinking. I just needed to breathe. My shoulders were so tense that it ached.

I thought this level was lying to me too, like all the others. There's always a catch, isn't there? What was I thinking? Did I have a death wish? It's never what it looks like. Something's obviously hiding in the forest. It's just gonna lure me in and then kill me the second I think I'm safe. One slip and it's over. Can't even trust a straight path to stay straight. And besides, my group needed me, didn't they? Was I not the only thing keeping them together?

There was nothing hiding in the forest.

It hadn't started snowing yet, but it was still so cold. Eventually I came across a clearing. There was a big patch on the ground with no grass or anything. There were others like it, not too far away, but I couldn't get over this one in particular. I didn't know why, but I stood there for a minute, staring at the sign nearby (even though it didn't have anything on it), then I started pacing. I couldn't get that kid out of my mind. Did I ever write about him?

Back when I was a kid in the Frontrooms, I went to some kind of lodge in a forest just like this one. I'm pretty sure it was a family trip. I was too young to remember much of it. But while we were there, I met this other kid, and we really hit it off. Our parents noticed and started talking (I assume), wanting to make sure we could meet up again. It turned out we lived right across the street from each other. By the next week, we were having a blast with each other every day.

I never saw him again after his house burned down. I was just a little kid, I didn't know what it meant. I don't know if he lived. I don't know if I could've done something. I can't even remember his name.

That's what I was thinking about in that clearing. I must've recognized the shape of the sign. Or was it the shape of the clearing?

I need to stop rambling. Only so much paper left.

It was getting dark, and it was cold enough to snow. I needed to either find a roof to put over my head, or set the tarp up in the trees and start a fire. Everything felt like it sucked. I wished things would be normal again, just once, just for a while. It was my responsibility to make sure of that, but I failed. I wanted to go back to those simpler, happier times.

I found a house right as it started to snow. I felt like I had a flashback when I saw it. That image, the shape of the house in the fire, it matched this one perfectly. It was his house, here in the Backrooms, like nothing ever happened. Then I snapped back and realized I was about to freeze. In hindsight, I really should have never trusted it. If it was a trap, I could've died in there. That's what this world wants of me.

Training kicked in and I had to clear the house. Part of me knew there would be nobody waiting for me. Except maybe something that wants to kill me, but there wasn't one of those either. Even though I swore I kept hearing something moving around. All I knew for sure is that the place looked about as lonely as I felt, and it was bigger on the inside. I found a fireplace, lit it up, then I collapsed on the couch.

A cozy fire in the empty house of a fleeting childhood friend that was consumed by the same thing. The only lights were the warm orange fire and the cold blue twilight. I fell asleep before I could start crying. God, stress takes a lot out of you.

If anyone is reading this, know that this is a good place to crash and burn. If you're going through a hard time, take the cold forest road and just breathe. Remember the good times. Look for the house. It's lonely, but it's safe.</div>

== <span class="header">Addendum 3</span> ==

Level 76 was one of the levels to be permanently affected by [[Phenomenon 12|The Flicker]] on February 1, 2016.

During the event, the level experienced a total blackout, endless night, constant blizzard, and moderate entity incursion, with confirmed sightings of [[Entity 3|Smilers]], [[Entity 16|Undying]], [[Entity 24|Refuses]], and [[Entity 83|Frigid Cone Spiders]]. All surviving explorers claimed that the road abruptly ended after some time, leaving them to wander through the forest unguided until they found the empty lots, which were also overtaken by trees. Those who chose to stay inside the house claim it did not have sufficient insulation from the sheer cold outside, that no new food appeared, and that entities would make regular attempts at entering.

Level 76 recovered from the Flicker on September 23, 2017, and as stated previously, it did not emerge unscathed. Although the main road no longer leads to any dead ends, swathes of it have become more derelict, showing large cracks, potholes, and other erosion that was observed during the Flicker. Some power lines have collapsed, and some of those that did remain live, occasionally preventing passage by threat of electrocution. The forest and the empty lots were completely unaffected.

The house is not without changes either. Instead of decaying along with the road, some individual instances of the house have become distorted; the layout may shift unexpectedly, with some windows and doors moving to unusual or nonsensical places. In all instances, objects are now able to infrequently appear, disappear, or move to another place when out of sight. Power outages occur more frequently during storms and last significantly longer, usually until the storm's end.

No personalized notes appeared during the Flicker, and they have become increasingly rare in the years since the level's recovery. Whereas the interval between finding notes used to be approximately one week, after the Flicker it has increased to roughly <s>two weeks (2017-12-19)</s> <s>four weeks (2020-04-16)</s> seven weeks (2024-12-29). The author of the messages has expressed a greater sense of guilt over the ruined state of Level 76.

[[Phenomenon 15]] was not lifted at any point during or after the Flicker.

== <span class="header">Addendum 4</span> ==

{{M.E.G Notice|notice=This section is marked for deletion.|reason=Do not upload personal logs to public database pages.}}
{{Login|username=user8327423423@bn0://thearchives.org|organization=M.E.G.|password=●●●●●●●●●●●●|body=<div class="light-borderblock">

I didn't expect my sins to catch up with me so soon. I really thought I would be able to hide until this all blows over. "Take the cold forest road," they said. Oh, how naïve I was.

Working for the [[M.E.G.]] in the position I'm at doesn't give me the best moral track record, I'll admit. I've always foolishly admired this group's work, pressuring others into joining them. All I can really say in my defense is that the pay is good. I know that's not enough.

I'll spare you the nitty-gritty. Yes, I went to Level 76 in the middle of the night. Yes, it took me longer than I wanted to find the house. Yes, I felt like I was being watched. No, I didn't find the house before it started snowing. In fact, it quickly turned into a blizzard. Yes, [[Object 5|Greek fire]] saved my sorry ass from frostbite.

There was a path leading into the forest. Not unusual, I thought, since there have been plenty of instances of the house being a little ways away from the other lots. There was a mailbox next to the street, and its flag was up. I looked inside, and there was a scrap of paper. I tried to read it as I was approaching the house. Key word 'tried'; it was dark and my hands were getting numb again.

It was a list of names. The more I read and reread them, the more I recognized them. They were the names of people I got to join the group. Last I heard, every last one of them was dead or missing.

I reached the end of the path right as I got to the handwriting in the corner.

''"I know what you are."''

There was no house.

I'm putting in my two weeks' notice.</div>}}

